From 103a1a1d7027d90eab7577a8860dba2b09e94ec6 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Frank Dana <ferdnyc@gmail.com>
Date: Thu, 11 Sep 2025 03:18:36 -0400
Subject: [PATCH] 100% coverage (#500)

* Tests: Clean up test_pydot.py

- Add a bunch of type annotations and defensive coding to eliminate
  red squiggles.
- Use `# pragma: no cover` and `# pragma: no branch` comments
  to exclude uncovered code that only runs when tests fail.
  (If those lines _do_ have coverage, it's a bad thing!)
- Remove some inheritable methods of the RenderResult subclasses

* test_pydot._compare_images: Rename 'pydot' arg to 'pd'

I don't know what I was thinking with that.

* Tests: from __future__ import annotations

And requisite changes to type annotations. Ruff is appeased.

* core: Annotate Dot.create() as returning bytes

Correct the declared return type of `create()`, which has never
returned a string (and couldn't possibly, since it produces
things like JPEG and PNG binary images).

This has knock-on effects for several other parts of the code,
though mostly they're positive ones. (I even got to remove a
`# type: ignore`, because the annotation is now correct.)

Other affected code:

* The generated `.create_*()` methods also now return `bytes`,
  of course.
* The return type of `call_graphviz()` becomes
  `tuple[bytes, bytes, subprocess.Popen[bytes]]`, because we
  were never passing in `universal_newlines` / `text` set to `True`.
* The `subprocess.Popen` _call_ that creates those return values
  becomes a call to a generic with `bytes` as the argument, in
  Python 3.9+. (I left a guard to protect earlier versions.)
* The `stdout_data` and `stderr_data` have to be decoded if we
  want to `print()` them.

* Tests: Add a test for parsing failure (bad input)

* Tests: Test FrozenDict.__repr__

* Tests: Test an invalid Graph(graph_type=) arg

Also completes the coverage on our exceptions module.

* Parser: pragma:no-branch some defensive conditions

A couple of if conditions are purely defensive, so they're always
True when running the tests. Mark them so they won't get scored as
incomplete branch coverage.

* Tests: More test coverage for graph modifications

Test more forms of add/get/del_edge
Test get_subgraph thoroughly
Test more forms of del_node

* More coverage: sequence, generated methods

Test get/set_attr() methods
Test create/write_format() methods

* Tests: Test failure modes of subprocess calls

* Tests: Test graph_from_edges

* Tests: Remaining coverage

Cover just about everything left, except some broken features

* Tests: Add some expected failures

Test a few features that DON'T work the way they should.
To help us keep track of them and hopefully motivate fixes.

* Coverage: pragmas, and explanatory comments

* Ruff fixes

* Tests: Don't use a negative return code

They're not portable between Windows and POSIX. Just exit(1) instead.

* Tests: Strip newlines for portability

* Tests: Eliminate PydotTestCase class

* Tests: Eliminate graph_directed fixture

It was too simple to be worth the trouble. The whole definition was:
`return pydot.Graph("testgraph", graph_type="digraph")`

And the name was soooo long to type.

* Remove some dead code from id_needs_quotes

* Tests: Test cluster obj_dict casting
